We installed cors support and enabled it in caravel following this instructions:
pip install -U flask-cors

The following keys in caravel_config.py can be specified to configure CORS:
    ENABLE_CORS: True
    CORS_OPTIONS:  without parameters

We want get the json from slices for example:
 https://example-domain.com:8088/caravel/explore/table/4/?slice_name=%25+RFC+Exitosos+-+1yr&y_axis_zero=y&resample_fillmethod=&show_brush=y&line_interpolation=linear&show_legend=y&resample_rule=&granularity_sqla=date{blablabla}e=kpm_measurements&contribution=false&time_grain_sqla=month&having=

Through ajax:

$.get(" https://example-domain.com:8088/caravel/explore/table/4/?slice_name=%25+RFC+Exitosos+-+1yr&y_axis_zero=y&resample_fillmethod=&show_brush=y&line_interpolation=linear&show_legend=y&resample_rule=&granularity_sqla=date{blablabla}e=kpm_measurements&contribution=false&time_grain_sqla=month&having=").done(function(response){
console.log(response);
});

So we created a new view method with @cross_origin(allow_headers=['Content-Type'], supports_credentials=True) and without the @has_access decorator to test and it works, but we want to know if there is a native alternative to expose a service for a REST client.

@ouoc Which version of Caravel are you using? This patch has been merged in 0.10 so if you are using it (or you have cloned the current master) you should be ok on this side.
Also, which version of Druid? Before 0.8.2 the issue that was preventing metadata pull is still present, so you have to wait one day before successfully pulling the metadata.
Finally, have you configured a MySQL server as the druid metadata storage? I haven't investigated the issue, but when using the Derby format (that is not suggested in production anyway) was causing Caravel to fail due to long response time on druid side. Using MySQL solved the issue (and many other Druid issue). We were on druid 0.8.3 at the time, though. Haven't tested on the 0.9.1 that we are using now.

Hi guys, I'd like to have a crack at implementing some join functionality at the table level. It wouldn't be a full "custom SQL" solution but it would allow some limited functionality for joining tables. 

My suggestion would be to create a new class as an extension of the current `SqlaTable` called something like `CompositeSqlaTable`. This would start with a base table (e.g. `customers`) and allow the joining of other tables to it (e.g. `orders`) with a choice of join options (left/right/inner/outer) and explicit specification of which field to use for joining on the left and right. The created composite table would then function and be queriable like a normal table at the moment in caravel (I guess it might be most sensible to autodetect columns from both sides of the join).

@mistercrunch thoughts on implementation/general idea? I know you mentioned a while back that you might be interested in limited join functionality.

@kartha01 @lerrua would this solve some of your pain points?

This would be massively helpful for me beyond using views, especially where the relevant datetime column for filtering is in a different table to the entity which I'm trying to query.
